A shopping application displays products in different categories.

When the user clicks on the Gifts category, the browser requests a URL like:
https://insecure-website.com/products?category=Gifts

This causes the application to make an SQL query to retrieve details of the relevant products from the database:
SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = 'Gifts' AND released = 1

It asks the database to return:

all details (*)
from the products table
where the category is Gifts
and where released = 1

The released = 1 restriction hides products that are not released.

If the application does not defend against SQL injection, an attacker can manipulate the category parameter.
https://insecure-website.com/products?category=Gifts'--
SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = 'Gifts'--' 

-- is a comment indicator in SQL, so the rest of the query is ignored.

That means the query no longer includes:

AND released = 1
So all products may be displayed, including unreleased products.



https://insecure-website.com/products?category=Gifts'+OR+1=1--
SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = 'Gifts' OR 1=1--
Because 1=1 is always true, the query can return all items.

Be careful when injecting OR 1=1 into a SQL query. Even if it looks harmless in one place, applications may reuse the same request data in multiple queries. If the condition reaches an UPDATE or DELETE statement, it could cause accidental data loss.

