If the application shows the results of a SQL query, an attacker can sometimes use SQL injection to retrieve data from other tables in the database.

The UNION keyword lets you execute an additional SELECT query and append the results to the original query.

Example original query

If an application executes the following query containing the user input Gifts:
SELECT name, description FROM products WHERE category = 'Gifts'

SELECT name, description → what data to show
FROM products → which table to read from
WHERE category = 'Gifts' → only rows that match the category

An attacker can submit:
' UNION SELECT username, password FROM users--
This changes the query to
SELECT name, description FROM products WHERE category = '' UNION SELECT username, password FROM users--';

What this does
UNION combines the results of two queries
the application may return usernames and passwords along with the product data
Important rule

The queries combined with UNION must have:

the same number of columns
compatible data types



Blind SQL injection vulnerabilites
- The application does not return the results of the SQL query or the details of any database errors within its responses
-Blind vulnerabilites can still be exploited to access unorthorised data but the techniques involed are more complicated

You can change the logic of the query to trigger a detectable difference in the application's response depending on the truth of a single condition. this might involve injecting a new condition into some Boolean logic, or condtionally triggering an error such as divide by zero

You can trigger a time delay in the processing of the query, this enables you ti infer the truth og the condition based on the time that the application takes to respond

You can trigger an out of band network interaction using OAST techniques. this technique works in situatios where others do not . you can directly exfiltrate data via the out of band channel , e.g. you can place the data into a DNS lookup for a domain that you control.

Second order SQL injection

First order SQL injection occurs when the application processes user input from an HTTP request and incorporates the input into a SQL query in an unsafe way.

Second order SQL injection occurs when the application takes user input from an HTTP request and storesit for future use. . this is usually done by placing the input into a databse., but no vulnerability occurs at the point where the data is stored. Later, when handling a different HTTP request, application retrieves the stroed data and incorporates it into a SQL query in an unsafe way.
this often occurs in situations where developers are aware of SQL injection vulnerabilites and so safely handle the initial placement of the input into the database . when the data is later processes, it is deemed to be safe since it was previously placed into the databse safely. at this point the data is handled in an unsafe way, because the developer wringly deems it to be trusted.

The hacker types something into a form, the website stores it safely and nothing bad happens yet. later the website readsthat stroed value and uses it in a new sql query unsafely.

Examining the database

Some core features of the SQL language are implemented in the same way across popular database platforms, and so many ways of detecting and exploiting SQL injection vulnerabilities work identically on different types of database.

However, there are also many differences between common databases. These mean that some techniques for detecting and exploiting SQL injection work differently on different platforms. For example:

Syntax for string concatenation.
Comments.
Batched (or stacked) queries.
Platform-specific APIs.
Error messages.

( some attacks work everywher,some attacks need to be adjusted based on the database)

Different databases are like different dialects:

Same core language (SQL)
Slightly different “accents” (syntax)

These usually work across most databases:

